		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31389555">A cool thing about art is its malleability in interpretation. Feel free to speculate on subject of the Mona Lisa, wonder if the infinite mirrors in Citizen Kane represent Charles' emptiness, and question if a cigar is just a cigar. But storytelling usually isn't riddled with riddles, and I'd guess most screenwriters and directors just focus on telling their story without loading the gun to the point of unwieldy.<br />
<br />
And that's how I want storytelling. Tell a story. A show or film that's all about a theme or message with no connection to the story is hollow (Ghost in the Shell comes to mind). It's like the screenwriter or director is too focused on pushing a message, to the point where the characters are a side-effect. To paraphrase Gareth Edwards, &quot;you should never start a story going <em>I'm going to make a movie about this theme</em>, but after a while you sort of discover what the film is about. This hidden thing that rises to the surface and says <em>this is what I'm really about.</em>&quot;<br />
<br />
I watch anime, or any film, because I'm expecting a story. I don't want storytelling integrity lost because the characters are nothing but vehicles for themes. Screenwriters and directors should make that concession to the audience keeping in mind it's entertainment first and foremost. It's for other people to watch, and they just have to hope enough people like it to give them incentive to go on; that's prolly part of why some genres are more niche than others. And that brings me to another angle I'm taking from the topic.<br />
<br />
When dealing with certain (any?) genres there's prolly some incentive to either focus on making the story work for what it is or try and reach out to a general audience. Once in a while we get something that forgoes the trade-off like The Dark Knight, but otherwise they lean toward one or the other. I'm cool with something for a general audience like J.J. Abrams Star Trek, and also enjoy some of the older Star Trek films the general audience has no patience for.<br />
<br />
So yah, I've got no problem with who their target audience is so long as the work itself is at least decent. This goes back to how the screenwriter or director should focus on storytelling instead of art or theme or whatever. The underlying message will appear if it's there, but sometimes, the director or screenwriter should just write a story about a traumatized pilot or magical girls suffering simply because they're sadistic bastards.<br />
<br />
<span style="text-decoration:line-through;">I get the feeling this topic has been done before under another guise.<!--strike--></span></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.imgur.com/vqw0XUz.png" /></div></td>
