		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31391775"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>iSuckAtWriting said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>Screenwriters and directors should make that concession to the audience keeping in mind it's entertainment first and foremost.<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
What do you think of the argument that writers shouldn't make something that they don't 'love' and that fewer people will love so that more people 'like' it?<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
As for my own opinion:<br />
<br />
When artists choose to do things their way and choose to speak to fewer people, I think it can lead to great things; however, although speaking to a more limited number of people has the potential to do great things, it doesn't mean it necessarily does just because it's more exclusive. <br />
<br />
Further, when a story restricts his audience, I don't think said audience's opinion is necessarily more valid or invalid than the rest of the crowd. IMO the opinion on Lucky Star of the person who's watched Haruhi is neither more valid than the newbie who didn't get the references. For examples, watchers missing the 'exclusive' content have be left with a flawed story the exclusivers overlooked but that the others can't be blamed for picking up on. I've talked with people for whom Ano Hana had an emotional value because they knew and liked the ED song from long before, with that cover of Secret Base being made ten years after its first release in accordance with the lyrics and the story being an homage to the song, and I while that's a move I have a lot of respect for, I found the story itself pretty bad. Worse, I think that actually trying to carry out the homage might have contributed to damaging the story in having Menma come back specifically ten years after her death for no real reason. <br />
<br />
The same thing goes for things like <!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/anime/23213/Kantoku_Fuyuki_Todoki">Kantoku Fuyuki Todoki</a>, which I enjoy far less/differently than those who're old enough to connect with the references. On the other hand, the Daicon openings' authenticy speaks to me in a somewhat personal way that I accept fully that will not matter to others. The same thing applies for references to literature, philosophy or religion. Evangelion might use Bible references, but does our knowledge of the Bible makes us righter than Japanese viewers who don't know about it? Plus, some of those who know the Bible might disagree among themselves about whether they're used cleverly or not -- again, just because part of the content is more restricted doesn't mean it's necessarily great, so defending content by simply saying that it was written with passion and authenticity is not a sufficient argument and you'd still have to explain what precisely about the exclusive content is great. If a big big modern-day otaku wrote his ideal of a story (e.g. <!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/anime/11757/Sword_Art_Online">on a fanfiction website</a>), with a harem and everything else, that does not make the opinion of people like us invalid by default. Nisio wrote exactly what he wanted to see in Nisemonogatari; it may not be pandering, but I still didn't like it.<br />
<br />
And, you know, I think that a lot of exclusive content can be inclusive without diluting your intent. Being exclusive is, in this regard, pretentious. A work that makes a lot of literature and philosophical references (imo in a good way but that's not the point), is SubaHibi, and it's very inclusive and unpretentious. It doesn't expect the viewer to know every single reference, and explains a lot of the philosophical parallels with specific authors and basics. It doesn't distract from the quality or dilutes the author's meaning; if anything, it enhances it. Remove all the explanations, and you're left with a bunch of characters who and speak in bad riddles and try hard to be cool. In other words, you'd be left with what I've seen from Kara no Kyoukai (basically just episode 1): inconsequential babble. Subarashiki Hibi and Kara no Kyoukai might both actually use philosophy references really intelligently for all we know, but when they're told like in the latter it's likely you won't be able to appreciate it anyway.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by lpf, 06-06-14, 8:01 PM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
