		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31495703">I believe that this talk by Jonathan Blow is relevant to this discussion, specifically the first 15 minutes or so where he talks about TV shows: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AxFzf6yIfcc" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AxFzf6yIfcc</a><br />
<br />
To summarize Blow's main talking points, early television shows were designed with several constraints.  The first of these was the &quot;commercial break:&quot; because television shows had interstitial advertisements, they had to have a cliffhanger at around the halfway mark to compel the audience to not change the channel during the few minutes that commercials were shown.  Another (perhaps more limiting) constraint was the fact that you couldn't assume a perfectly regular audience.  The lack of consumer recording technology meant that if someone missed an episode, there was no way for them to &quot;catch up&quot; after a missed episode until the reruns ran months later.  It wasn't until the 1980's that VCR technology became mainstream.  As such, TV writers could not have &quot;indispensable&quot; episodes.  And as a consequence, all shows were episodic rather than serial in nature.  A heavily story-driven show like Game of Thrones or Breaking Bad could not exist in 1970.<br />
<br />
Even shows from the early era of television that I consider &quot;good&quot; are undeniably hampered by these constraints: Star Trek TOS (1966-1969) episodes are incredibly formulaic, with the same dramatic stingers timed in accordance with the placement of commercial breaks.  Because the show is structured so that the episodes can be watched in any order and any episode can be skipped, you know that there is zero risk of any of the main crew members dying (and it is also highly probable that any new character that has just been introduced is at high risk of dying when the writers want to raise the stakes).  To be clear, I don't believe that formulas are inherently bad, and the strength of the Star Trek formula is a large part what made it an enjoyable show, and it's what allowed a show with a large staff of writers to remain thematically consistent for the most part.  For an interesting read, check out this Star Trek Writers Guide: <a href="http://www.bu.edu/clarion/guides/Star_Trek_Writers_Guide.pdf" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.bu.edu/clarion/guides/Star_Trek_Writers_Guide.pdf</a><br />
<br />
All of this of course applies to anime as well.<br />
<br />
There are some medium constraints that we take for granted.  For example, most anime are made for a TV viewing audience, and as a result they are produced to fit into a 30 minute broadcast time slot, which means 25 airing time including the OP and ED.  OP and ED are 90 seconds long each (a mostly arbitrary convention), so that means 22 minutes are dedicated to the actual episode, with very little flexibility.  But what if the creator wants to create an episode that is not exactly 22 minutes in length?  What if they only have 15 minutes of material, and have to come up with another 7 minutes of filler to pad it out?  Again, this is another place where manga adaptations are frequently at a disadvantage when the creators try to do a strict 1:1 chapter:episode ratio, because frequently it means turning a 10-15 minute read into a 25-minute viewing experience.  Some early shounen anime are notoriously bad about this.<br />
<br />
The time constraint problem can work in the opposite direction as well.  For example, Detective Conan tries to avoid the filler problem by splitting each episode into two 12-minute segments, each covering a single mystery.  But sometimes, the running time isn't long enough to properly encapsulate all the details that were present in the manga.  And for a mystery story like Detective Conan, that's sometimes a problem, because sometimes omitting a small clue can make the story's conclusion seem illogical.<br />
<br />
Further on the subject of timing and television show logistics, episode count is another thing to consider.  TV shows are made to broadcast for a single season, meaning that they typically air in chunks of 12-13 or 24-26 episodes.  But what if the story the anime is trying to tell is better suited to a different episode count?  What if the story has enough content to be told in exactly 15 episodes?  (Bakemonogatari sort of got around this by doing a 12-episode TV broadcast and then airing the last 3 episodes online.)  I also feel that there are a lot of 12-episode anime that might function better if they were shorter; I think we've all seen anime that don't have nearly enough content to justify their episode count.<br />
<br />
There are other cases where audience considerations constrain anime creators, particularly adaptive works.  Anime that are based on manga, light novels, or visual novels frequently must be created to appease the fans of the original work.  In some cases, you have scenes that work well in the light novel medium, but don't translate well to the more visual medium of anime.  For example, non-animated media often have longer expository sequences that are necessary to explain things that can't effectively be conveyed through visuals.  As a result, you have anime that doesn't fully utilize the freedom afforded by its own medium.<br />
<br />
On the subject of manga, I found Bakuman to be a particularly instructive work (in its content, not its presentation) because it describes the manga-making process (or at least how making manga for Shounen Jump works) in a way that makes it very clear how the Shounen Jump &quot;formula&quot; came to be.  Authors, on a week to week basis, must retain the interest of their readership.  And this often guides the direction of their storytelling.  I've noticed that some cases, serialized manga tends to short-circuit the typical storytelling cycle of rising and falling action, because when you're being judged on a weekly basis, there is no time for falling action.  Some established mangaka are able to break free of this to a certain extent, as a long-running series is less likely to be canceled even if there is a lull for a &quot;slow burn,&quot; but that's something that mangaka must earn through reputation (both their own reputation and the reputation of their work).</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
