		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31640495">I think what is important with art is not what the artist wants it to say, but rather what the audience gets from the work of art. For example, Bakemonogatari probably says some interesting stuff about life and death, morality and all that other philosophical stuff. Unfortunately, it's presented in a way that does not appeal to me; the otaku pandering route. I therefore am not able to see the way the writer wants me to see, but rather I see just another otaku pandering piece of work.<br />
<br />
This leads to the question I suppose. Should an artist water down their work for the audience to understand? If we go by my example, I would definitely say no. However, the reverse can just as easily work. An anime blogger by the name of E-Minor demonstrates my point perfectly. I hope he doesn't mind this link to his post.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://moesucks.com/2012/07/31/in-defense-of-guilty-crown/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://moesucks.com/2012/07/31/in-defense-of-guilty-crown/</a><br />
<br />
Here he defends Guilty Crown; an anime which is regarded by the majority of non-casual anime fans as one of the most disappointing anime of recent years. While most people see Guilty Crown as a cynical attempt to cash in on big budget action with little regard to plot, E-Minor sees this as a satire (and he defends his point well, I think I've been convinced, but I'll need to rewatch to confirm) which actually has some interesting things to say about the nature of people's tastes in their entertainment.<br />
<br />
So yes, I believe if the artist has a message to convey and wants it to reach a larger audience than it might if it was presented in it's &quot;purest&quot; form, it's not the worst idea in the world. After all, we get stuff like Bakemonogatari and Guilty Crown that are on opposite ends of the spectrum in terms of critical acclaim, yet to me are inverse in the amount of meaning it has. It's presentation might not appeal to everyone, but if it appeals to even one more person than it would have without this &quot;watered down&quot; form, is it not all the more worth it that people get the message? They might not be able to decode the message like me with Monogatari, but it's been sent and regardless of how it's interpreted, getting your work out there is what you want in the end is it not?<br />
<br />
Though then again, I remember watching a the film Free2Play and one of the developers was sad that people couldn't discern the message of his game. So maybe what I wrote is moot, or perhaps it isn't. Perhaps it depends on the artist? Who knows? As long as we keep getting our entertainment with real substance though, I can't complain.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
