		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31750593">I am firmly in the camp of<br />
<div class="quotetext">should they try to bring their vision to life in the purest form possible and accept that it will only resonate with a smaller audience<!--quote--></div><br />
this.<br />
<br />
Of course this can still entail catering to certain audiences. That can simply be a part of your vision (or rather, happen to be. A personal 'vision' does not automatically mean abstract/avant-garde). Or it can be the most abstract thing in the world.<br />
Art is a personal thing, and unless it's entirely a money-minded studio production (see: all LN adaptations and the like), then it will be in one way or another an attempt at someone's vision, or a vision spread across multiple poeple.<br />
<br />
This entire topic immediately makes me think of Aku no Hana - the anime. This is a prime example of someone, in this case Nagahama Hiroshi, following through with HIS vision, knowing full well that it would bomb and be heavily criticised, as he says....<br />
&quot;I knew there was going to be criticism before it aired, because I picked a way to do this anime that people will be critical about. People were saying it looks creepy, but I think it's better to feel something than nothing at all.&quot;<br />
<br />
Of course this same idea applies to pretty much any avant-garde anime. Cat Soup. Mind Game. The works of Yamamura Kouji. End of Evangelion. Mononoke.<br />
Some are more successful than others, but all of them are made, or seem to be made, with only the work itself in mind. And I think they are all in some way a form of personal expression. Of course the degree to which this is so varies heavily (EoE vs Mononoke, for example).</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
